				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body" aria-labelledby=3D"firstH=
eading" data-mw-ve-target-container=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Coo=
rdinates comprising a distance and an angle</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Examples_of_Polar_Coordinates.svg" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/d/d3/Examples_of_Polar_Coordinates.svg/250px-Examples_of_Polar_Co=
ordinates.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"186" class=3D=
"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"813" data-file-height=3D"605"></a><fig=
caption>Points in the polar coordinate system with pole <i>O</i> and polar =
axis <i>L</i>. In green, the point with radial coordinate 3 and angular coo=
rdinate 60 degrees or (3,<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>60=C2=B0). In =
blue, the point (4,<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>210=C2=B0).</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>polar coordinate system</b> specifies a give=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Point (mathematics)">point</a> in a <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(mathematics)" title=3D"Plane (mathematics)">pl=
ane</a> by using a distance and an angle as its two <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordinate=
s</a>. These are
</p>
<ul><li>the point's distance from a reference point called the <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pole_and_polar" title=3D"Pole and polar">=
pole</a></i>, and</li>
<li>the point's direction from the pole relative to the direction of the <i=
>polar axis</i>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_(geometry)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ray (geometry)">ray</a> drawn from the pole=
.</li></ul>
<p>The distance from the pole is called the <i>radial coordinate</i>, <i>ra=
dial distance</i> or simply <i>radius</i>, and the angle is called the <i>a=
ngular coordinate</i>, <i>polar angle</i>, or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Azimuth" title=3D"Azimuth">azimuth</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-brown_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-brown-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The pole is analogous=
 to the origin in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coor=
dinate_system" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian coordinate s=
ystem</a>.
</p><p>Polar coordinates are most appropriate in any context where the phen=
omenon being considered is inherently tied to direction and length from a c=
enter point in a plane, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sp=
iral" title=3D"Spiral">spirals</a>. Planar physical systems with bodies mov=
ing around a central point, or phenomena originating from a central point, =
are often simpler and more intuitive to model using polar coordinates.
</p><p>The polar coordinate system is extended to three dimensions in two w=
ays: the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylindrical_coordinate_sy=
stem" title=3D"Cylindrical coordinate system">cylindrical coordinate system=
</a> adds a second distance coordinate, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system" title=3D"Spherical coordinate sy=
stem">spherical coordinate system</a> adds a second angular coordinate.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gr%C3%A9goire_de_Saint-Vinc=
ent" title=3D"Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent">Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincen=
t</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventura_Cavalieri" t=
itle=3D"Bonaventura Cavalieri">Bonaventura Cavalieri</a> independently intr=
oduced the system's concepts in the mid-17th century, though the actual ter=
m <i>polar coordinates</i> has been attributed to <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gregorio_Fontana" title=3D"Gregorio Fontana">Gregorio Fonta=
na</a> in the 18th century. The initial motivation for introducing the pola=
r system was the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular=
_motion" title=3D"Circular motion">circular</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Orbital_motion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orbital mo=
tion">orbital motion</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolar_coordinate_syste=
m&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Head_of_Hipparchus_(cropped).jpg" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/c/c6/Head_of_Hipparchus_%28cropped%29.jpg/250px-Head_of_Hipparchus=
_%28cropped%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"249" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"434" data-file-height=3D"540"></a><=
figcaption>Hipparchus, Greek astronomer</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concepts of angle and radius were already used by ancient peoples of=
 the first millennium <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Before_Chris=
t" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Before Christ">BC</a>. The Greek astronom=
er <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hipparchus" title=3D"Hipparchus=
">Hipparchus</a> (190=E2=80=93120 BC) created a table of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chord_(geometry)" title=3D"Chord (geometry)">chord</=
a> functions giving the length of the chord for each angle, and there are r=
eferences to his using polar coordinates in establishing stellar positions.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_Spirals" title=3D"On Spirals">On Spirals</a=
></i>, Greek mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archime=
des" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> describes <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Archimedean_spiral" title=3D"Archimedean spiral">his spira=
l</a>, a function whose radius depends on the angle. The Greek work, howeve=
r, did not extend to a full coordinate system.
</p><p>From the 8th century AD onward, astronomers developed methods for ap=
proximating and calculating the direction to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mecca" title=3D"Mecca">Mecca</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Qibla" title=3D"Qibla">qibla</a>)=E2=80=94and its distance=E2=80=
=94from any location on the Earth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-king_3-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#c=
ite_note-king-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> From the 9th century onward they were using <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_trigonometry" title=3D"Sphe=
rical trigonometry">spherical trigonometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Map_projection" title=3D"Map projection">map projection</a=
> methods to determine these quantities accurately. The calculation is esse=
ntially the conversion of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geod=
etic_coordinates#Coordinates" title=3D"Geodetic coordinates">equatorial pol=
ar coordinates</a> of Mecca (i.e. its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Longitude" title=3D"Longitude">longitude</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Latitude" title=3D"Latitude">latitude</a>) to its polar =
coordinates (i.e. its qibla and distance) relative to a system whose refere=
nce meridian is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_circle" =
title=3D"Great circle">great circle</a> through the given location and the =
Earth's poles and whose polar axis is the line through the location and its=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antipodal_point" title=3D"Antipod=
al point">antipodal point</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-4"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>There are various accounts of the introduction of polar coordinates =
as part of a formal coordinate system. The full history of the subject is d=
escribed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard_University" ti=
tle=3D"Harvard University">Harvard</a> professor <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Julian_Lowell_Coolidge" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Julia=
n Lowell Coolidge">Julian Lowell Coolidge</a>'s <i>Origin of Polar Coordina=
tes.</i> Mathematicians from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesui=
ts" title=3D"Jesuits">Jesuit</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gr%C3%A9goire_de_Saint-Vincent" title=3D"Gr=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent">Gr=
=C3=A9goire de Saint-Vincent</a>, and Italian <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bonaventura_Cavalieri" title=3D"Bonaventura Cavalieri">Bonavent=
ura Cavalieri</a> independently introduced the concepts in the mid-seventee=
nth century. Saint-Vincent wrote about them privately in 1625 and published=
 his work in 1647, while Cavalieri published his in 1635, with a corrected =
version appearing in 1653. Cavalieri first used polar coordinates to solve =
a problem relating to the area within an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Archimedean_spiral" title=3D"Archimedean spiral">Archimedean spiral<=
/a>. French mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_P=
ascal" title=3D"Blaise Pascal">Blaise Pascal</a> subsequently used polar co=
ordinates to calculate the length of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabolic arcs</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cool=
idge_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pola=
r_coordinate_system#cite_note-coolidge-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_Fluxions" t=
itle=3D"Method of Fluxions">Method of Fluxions</a></i> (written 1671, publi=
shed 1736), English mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Sir Isaac Newton</a> examined the tran=
sformations between polar coordinates, which he referred to as the "Seventh=
 Manner; For Spirals", and nine other coordinate systems.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-boyer_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
olar_coordinate_system#cite_note-boyer-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He is credited with or=
iginating the polar coordinate system in its analytic form and for originat=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipolar_coordinates" title=3D"=
Bipolar coordinates">bipolar coordinates</a> in a strict sense.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pol=
ar_coordinate_system#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the journal <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acta_Eruditorum" title=3D"Acta Eruditorum">Act=
a Eruditorum</a></i> (1691), Swiss mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Bernoulli" title=3D"Jacob Bernoulli">Jacob Bernoulli</=
a> used a system with a point on a line, called the <i>pole</i> and <i>pola=
r axis</i> respectively. Coordinates were specified by the distance from th=
e pole and the angle from the <i>polar axis</i>. Bernoulli's work extended =
to the calculation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radius_o=
f_curvature_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radius of curvatu=
re (mathematics)">radius of curvature</a> of curves expressed in these coor=
dinates.
</p><p>The term <i>polar coordinates</i> was attributed to <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregorio_Fontana" title=3D"Gregorio Fontana">Grego=
rio Fontana</a> and used by 18th-century Italian writers. The term appeared=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language" title=3D"Eng=
lish language">English</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geor=
ge_Peacock_(mathematician)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"George Peacock (=
mathematician)">George Peacock</a>'s 1816 translation of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylvestre_Fran%C3%A7ois_Lacroix" title=3D"Sylvestre =
Fran=C3=A7ois Lacroix">Lacroix</a>'s <i>Differential and Integral Calculus<=
/i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_=
coordinate_system#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Alexis_Clairaut" title=3D"Alexis Clairaut">Alexis Clairaut</a> was =
the first to think of polar coordinates in three dimensions, and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leo=
nhard Euler</a> was the first to actually develop them.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
coolidge_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-coolidge-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
