-align: -0.838ex; width:15.973ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r=
=3D\sin(6\!\cdot \!\theta )+2}"></span>. Click on image for details.</figca=
ption></figure><p>The equation defining a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Plane_curve" title=3D"Plane curve">plane curve</a> expressed in pol=
ar coordinates is known as a <i>polar equation</i>. In many cases, such an =
equation can simply be specified by defining <i>r</i> as a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathema=
tics)">function</a> of <i>=CF=86</i>. The resulting curve then consists of =
points of the form (<i>r</i>(<i>=CF=86</i>),&nbsp;<i>=CF=86</i>) and can be=
 regarded as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_of_a_functi=
on" title=3D"Graph of a function">graph</a> of the polar function <i>r</i>.=
 Note that, in contrast to Cartesian coordinates, the independent variable =
<i>=CF=86</i> is the <i>second</i> entry in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ordered_pair" title=3D"Ordered pair">ordered pair</a>.
</p><p>Different forms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry=
" title=3D"Symmetry">symmetry</a> can be deduced from the equation of a pol=
ar function <i>r</i>:
</p>
<ul><li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i>(=E2=88=92<i>=CF=86</i>) =3D <i>=
r</i>(<i>=CF=86</i>)</span> the curve will be symmetrical about the horizon=
tal (0=C2=B0/180=C2=B0) ray;</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i>(<i>=CF=80</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=CF=86</=
i>) =3D <i>r</i>(<i>=CF=86</i>)</span> it will be symmetric about the verti=
cal (90=C2=B0/270=C2=B0) ray:</li>
<li>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i>(<i>=CF=86</i> =E2=88=92 =CE=B1) =3D=
 <i>r</i>(<i>=CF=86</i>)</span> it will be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Rotational_symmetry" title=3D"Rotational symmetry">rotationally sy=
mmetric</a> by =CE=B1 clockwise and counterclockwise about the pole.</li></=
ul>
<p>Because of the circular nature of the polar coordinate system, many curv=
es can be described by a rather simple polar equation, whereas their Cartes=
ian form is much more intricate. Among the best known of these curves are t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rose_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ro=
se (mathematics)">polar rose</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Archimedean_spiral" title=3D"Archimedean spiral">Archimedean spiral</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemniscate_of_Bernoulli" title=3D"Le=
mniscate of Bernoulli">lemniscate</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Lima%C3%A7on" title=3D"Lima=C3=A7on">lima=C3=A7on</a>, and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardioid" title=3D"Cardioid">cardioid</a>.
</p><p>For the circle, line, and polar rose below, it is understood that th=
ere are no restrictions on the domain and range of the curve.
</p>
