        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>a</mi>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle r(\varphi )=
=3Da+b\varphi .}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b6bc07b3412232dc537a723cc05e6cb670c6bb08" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:14.711ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r=
(\varphi )=3Da+b\varphi .}"></span>
Changing the parameter <i>a</i> will turn the spiral, while <i>b</i> contro=
ls the distance between the arms, which for a given spiral is always consta=
nt. The Archimedean spiral has two arms, one for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>=CF=86</i> &gt; 0</span> and one for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i>=
 &lt; 0</span>. The two arms are smoothly connected at the pole. If <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i> =3D 0</span>, taking the mirror image of one arm =
across the 90=C2=B0/270=C2=B0 line will yield the other arm. This curve is =
notable as one of the first curves, after the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Conic_section" title=3D"Conic section">conic sections</a>, to b=
e described in a mathematical treatise, and as a prime example of a curve b=
est defined by a polar equation.
</p>
