ing frame</h5><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPo=
lar_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Co-rotating frame"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For a particle in planar motion, one approach to attaching physical sign=
ificance to these terms is based on the concept of an instantaneous <i>co-r=
otating frame of reference</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Taylor_27-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#c=
ite_note-Taylor-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To define a co-rotating frame, first an ori=
gin is selected from which the distance <i>r</i>(<i>t</i>) to the particle =
is defined. An axis of rotation is set up that is perpendicular to the plan=
e of motion of the particle, and passing through this origin. Then, at the =
selected moment <i>t</i>, the rate of rotation of the co-rotating frame =CE=
=A9 is made to match the rate of rotation of the particle about this axis, =
<i>d=CF=86</i>/<i>dt</i>. Next, the terms in the acceleration in the inerti=
al frame are related to those in the co-rotating frame. Let the location of=
 the particle in the inertial frame be (<i>r</i>(<i>t</i>), <i>=CF=86</i>(<=
i>t</i>)), and in the co-rotating frame be (<i>r</i>=E2=80=B2(t), <i>=CF=86=
</i>=E2=80=B2(t)). Because the co-rotating frame rotates at the same rate a=
s the particle, <i>d=CF=86</i>=E2=80=B2/<i>dt</i> =3D 0. The fictitious cen=
trifugal force in the co-rotating frame is <i>mr</i>=CE=A9<sup>2</sup>, rad=
ially outward. The velocity of the particle in the co-rotating frame also i=
s radially outward, because <i>d=CF=86</i>=E2=80=B2/<i>dt</i> =3D 0. The <i=
>fictitious Coriolis force</i> therefore has a value =E2=88=922<i>m</i>(<i>=
dr</i>/<i>dt</i>)=CE=A9, pointed in the direction of increasing <i>=CF=86</=
i> only. Thus, using these forces in Newton's second law we find:
