ation (multiplied by the mass of the particle) as found in the inertial fra=
me as the negative of the centrifugal and Coriolis forces that would be see=
n in the instantaneous, non-inertial co-rotating frame.
</p><p>For general motion of a particle (as opposed to simple circular moti=
on), the centrifugal and Coriolis forces in a particle's frame of reference=
 commonly are referred to the instantaneous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Osculating_circle" title=3D"Osculating circle">osculating circle<=
/a> of its motion, not to a fixed center of polar coordinates. For more det=
ail, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centripetal_force#Local_c=
oordinates" title=3D"Centripetal force">centripetal force</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Differential_geometry">Diff=
erential geometry</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DPolar_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"=
Edit section: Differential geometry"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the modern terminology of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
fferential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geometry<=
/a>, polar coordinates provide <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coo=
rdinate_charts" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coordinate charts">coordinat=
e charts</a> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiabl=
e_manifold" title=3D"Differentiable manifold">differentiable manifold</a> <=
span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b><sup>2</sup> \ {(0,0)}</span>, the plane min=
us the origin. In these coordinates, the Euclidean <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Metric_tensor" title=3D"Metric tensor">metric tensor</a> i=
s given by<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span cla=
ss=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;=
"><math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" altt=
ext=3D"{\displaystyle ds^{2}=3Ddr^{2}+r^{2}d\theta ^{2}.}">
