<p>Polar coordinates can also be extended into three dimensions using the c=
oordinates (=CF=81, =CF=86, =CE=B8), where =CF=81 is the distance from the =
pole, =CF=86 is the angle from the z-axis (called the colatitude or zenith =
and measured from 0 to 180=C2=B0), and =CE=B8 is the angle from the x-axis =
(as in the polar coordinates). This coordinate system, called the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system" title=3D"Sph=
erical coordinate system">spherical coordinate system</a>, is similar to th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latitude" title=3D"Latitude">lat=
itude</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitude" title=3D"=
Longitude">longitude</a> system used for Earth, with the latitude =CE=B4 be=
ing the complement of =CF=86, determined by =CE=B4 =3D 90=C2=B0 =E2=88=92 =
=CF=86, and the longitude <i>l</i> being measured by <i>l</i> =3D =CE=B8 =
=E2=88=92 180=C2=B0. <sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-28"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The three spherical coordinates are converted to Cartesian coordinat=
es by
</p>
