<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolar_coordi=
nate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Appl=
ications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>Polar coordinates are two-dimensional and thus they can be used only whe=
re point positions lie on a single two-dimensional plane. They are most app=
ropriate in any context where the phenomenon being considered is inherently=
 tied to direction and length from a center point. For instance, the exampl=
es above show how elementary polar equations suffice to define curves=E2=80=
=94such as the Archimedean spiral=E2=80=94whose equation in the Cartesian c=
oordinate system would be much more intricate. Moreover, many physical syst=
ems=E2=80=94such as those concerned with bodies moving around a central poi=
nt or with phenomena originating from a central point=E2=80=94are simpler a=
nd more intuitive to model using polar coordinates. The initial motivation =
for the introduction of the polar system was the study of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_motion" title=3D"Circular motion">circular=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbital_motion" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Orbital motion">orbital motion</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Position_and_navigation">Po=
sition and navigation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPolar_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=
=3D"Edit section: Position and navigation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Polar coordinates are used often in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Navigation" title=3D"Navigation">navigation</a> as the destination or =
direction of travel can be given as an angle and distance from the object b=
eing considered. For instance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air=
craft" title=3D"Aircraft">aircraft</a> use a slightly modified version of t=
he polar coordinates for navigation. In this system, the one generally used=
 for any sort of navigation, the 0=C2=B0 ray is generally called heading 36=
0, and the angles continue in a clockwise direction, rather than counterclo=
ckwise, as in the mathematical system. Heading 360 corresponds to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_north" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Magnetic north">magnetic north</a>, while headings 90, 180, and 270 c=
orrespond to magnetic east, south, and west, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_c=
oordinate_system#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Thus, an aircraft traveling 5 na=
utical miles due east will be traveling 5 units at heading 90 (read <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ICAO_spelling_alphabet" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"ICAO spelling alphabet">zero-niner-zero</a> by <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_traffic_control" title=3D"Air traffic contro=
l">air traffic control</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-30"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modeling">Modeling</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPolar_coordinate_sys=
tem&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Modeling"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>Systems displaying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_symme=
try" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radial symmetry">radial symmetry</a> pr=
ovide natural settings for the polar coordinate system, with the central po=
int acting as the pole. A prime example of this usage is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Groundwater_flow_equation" title=3D"Groundwater =
flow equation">groundwater flow equation</a> when applied to radially symme=
tric wells. Systems with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central=
_force" title=3D"Central force">radial force</a> are also good candidates f=
or the use of the polar coordinate system. These systems include <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Gravitation">gravitational fields</a>, which obey the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse-square_law" title=3D"Inverse-square law">invers=
e-square law</a>, as well as systems with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Point_source" title=3D"Point source">point sources</a>, such as <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antenna_(radio)" title=3D"Antenna (ra=
dio)">radio antennas</a>.
</p><p>Radially asymmetric systems may also be modeled with polar coordinat=
es. For example, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microphone" tit=
le=3D"Microphone">microphone</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Microphone_pick_up_patterns" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microphone pic=
k up patterns">pickup pattern</a> illustrates its proportional response to =
an incoming sound from a given direction, and these patterns can be represe=
nted as polar curves. The curve for a standard cardioid microphone, the mos=
t common unidirectional microphone, can be represented as <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><i>r</i> =3D 0.5 + 0.5sin(<i>=CF=95</i>)</span> at its target design =
frequency.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-eargle_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system#cite_note-eargle-31"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> The pattern shifts toward omnidirectionality at lower frequencie=
s.
</p>
